{"title_page": "Laurence Olivier Award", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name        = The Olivier Awards\n| current_awards = 2020 Laurence Olivier Awards\n| image       = \n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Laurence Olivier Award, designed by the sculptor Harry Franchetti.  It depicts Olivier as Henry V at the [[Old Vic]] in 1937.\n| description = Best in London theatre\n| presenter   = [[Society of London Theatre]]\n| country     = [[United Kingdom]]\n| year        = {{start date and age|1976}}\n| website     = https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/\n}}\n\nThe '''Laurence Olivier Awards''', or simply the '''Olivier Awards''', are presented annually by the [[Society of London Theatre]] to recognise excellence in professional theatre in [[London]] at an annual ceremony in the capital. The awards were originally known as the '''Society of West End Theatre Awards''', but they were renamed in honour of the British actor [[Laurence Olivier]] in 1984.\n\nThe awards are given to individuals involved in [[West End theatre|West End]] productions and other leading [[West End theatre#London's non-commercial theatres|non-commercial theatres]] based in London across a range of categories covering plays, musicals, dance, opera and affiliate theatre. A discretionary non-competitive Special Olivier Award is also given each year. The Olivier Awards are recognised internationally as the highest honour in British theatre, equivalent to the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] Awards for film and television, and the [[Brit Awards|BRIT Awards]] for music. The Olivier Awards are considered equivalent to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]'s [[Tony Award]]s and [[France]]'s [[Moli\u00e8re Award]].\n\nSince its inception, the awards have been held at various venues and theatres across London, from 2012-2016 at the [[Royal Opera House]], before moving to the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 2017. Television coverage is broadcast in prime time on ITV, who acquired the rights from 2013 onwards with radio coverage by [[Magic Radio (London radio station)|Magic Radio]].\n\n==History==\nThe awards were first established in 1976 by the Society of London Theatre as the Society of West End Awards and were designed by artist Tom Merrifield. In 1984, British actor [[Laurence Olivier]] gave his consent for the awards to be renamed in his honour and they became known as the Laurence Olivier Awards.<ref>[https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/10-things-probably-didnt-know-olivier-awards/ \"10 Things You Probably Didn't Know About The Olivier Awards\"]. OfficialLondonTheatre.com, accessed 30 January 2018</ref> The [[1976 Laurence Olivier Awards|first awards ceremony]] was held in December 1976 at [[Hotel Caf\u00e9 Royal|Caf\u00e9 Royal]].\n\n==Judging==\nEach year, Olivier Awards judging panels for theatre, opera, dance and affiliate shows are put together by the [[Society of London Theatre|Society of London Theatre (SOLT)]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/choosing-the-winners/|title=How the Olivier Award winners are chosen - Olivier Awards|work=Official London Theatre|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nFor opera, dance and affiliates, each panel are made up of a mix of \u2018professional\u2019 panellists (journalists, casting directors, arts administrators, publishers and other industry professionals chosen for their knowledge in the field) and members of the public who are passionate about London theatre. The panels first select the shows they consider most worthy of an Olivier Award nomination, then vote on a winner at the end of the judging period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFor the theatre awards, a longlist is compiled by a panel made up of members of the public, and submitted to SOLT members to vote on. Members may still vote outside of the list at this stage, except for in the four Supporting Actor/Actress categories (as these each contain thousands of eligible performers). The members\u2019 votes are collated with those of the panellists to create the list of nominees. The nominees list is then voted on by both members and panellists to produce the winners.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Ceremony==\n\n===Hosts and Presenters===\nPrevious hosts of the Olivier Awards ceremony include [[Michael Ball]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Clive Anderson]], [[Gemma Arterton]], [[Stephen Mangan]], [[Hugh Bonneville]], [[Sheridan Smith]], [[Lenny Henry]], [[Catherine Tate]] and [[Jason Manford]].\n\nPresenters of individual awards include [[Anthony Head]], [[James Nesbitt]], [[Richard E. Grant]], [[Richard Wilson (Scottish actor)|Richard Wilson]], [[Sue Johnston]], [[Angela Lansbury]], [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], [[Eddie Izzard]], Sir [[Tom Stoppard]], [[Barry Norman]], [[Peter Barkworth]], [[Daniel Radcliffe]], [[Anthony Hopkins]], [[Sue Lawley]], [[Diana Rigg]], [[Edward Fox (actor)|Edward Fox]], [[Tim Rice]], [[Gary Wilmot]], [[Jane Asher]], [[Tom Conti]], [[Denis Quilley]], [[Angela Rippon]], [[Cuba Gooding Jr.]], [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]], [[Patti LuPone]], [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[John Boyega]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Meera Syal]], [[Paul O'Grady]], [[Julian Clary]] and [[Juliet Stevenson]].<ref name=facts>[http://www.olivierawards.com/about/facts-and-trivia/ \"Olivier Awards Facts\"]. Olivierawards.com, accessed 7 February 2011</ref>\n\n===Venues===\nThe venue most associated with the Awards is [[Grosvenor House Hotel]], which has housed the after-show reception nine times and hosted the whole event on four further occasions. As well as at the Grosvenor, the presentations have been held at: Victoria Palace, Lyceum, National Theatre Olivier, Albery (now No\u00ebl Coward), Shaftesbury, London Palladium, Dominion, Royalty, [[Theatre Royal Drury Lane]],<ref name=playbill>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147401-Love-Never-Dies-Legally-Blonde-Rylance-Jacobi-Boggess-Bennett-End-of-the-Rainbow-Are-Olivier-Nominees \"Love Never Dies, Legally Blonde, Rylance, Jacobi, Boggess, Bennett, End of the Rainbow Are Olivier Nominees\"]. Playbill.com, February 7, 2011</ref> Caf\u00e9 Royal, Piccadilly, and The Park Lane Hilton.\n\nFrom [[2012 Laurence Olivier Awards|2012 to 2016]] the awards ceremony was held at the [[Royal Opera House]], moving to the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 2017.<ref name=\"Who Won at The Olivier Awards 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/the-olivier-awards-2017 | title= Who Won at The Olivier Awards 2017 | publisher=Ikon London Magazine | last1 = Alvarez | first1 = Joe | last2 = Orlova-Alvarez | first2 = Tamara | date=10 April 2017 | accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/how-it-all-began/|title=Olivier Awards - How It All Began|website=OfficialLondonTheatre.com|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref> The 2013 ceremony was the first ceremony to be broadcast on television since 2003.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jan/29/olivier-awards-return-to-tv|title=Olivier awards make triumphant return to TV|first=Matt|last=Trueman|date=29 January 2013|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe first Laurence Olivier Awards to be broadcast on television was the 1981 ceremony, which was broadcast on BBC1, and continued every year until 1992, before switching to BBC2 each year until 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westendtheatre.com/16310/the-olivier-awards/awards-history/|title=Olivier Awards \u2013 HistoryLondon theatre tickets - London theatre tickets|website=www.westendtheatre.com}}</ref> The awards ceremony was then only broadcast on radio until 2011, when the BBC broadcast live interactive red-button coverage of the event,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2011/mar/14/olivier-awards-bbc-coverage-ceremony|title=Olivier theatre awards: the BBC should be red-faced over its red-button coverage|first=Carrie|last=Dunn|date=14 March 2011|website=the Guardian}}</ref> while [[Paul Gambaccini]] presented a programme on [[BBC Radio 2]] with live coverage and interviews.<ref name=playbill/> The same coverage followed in 2012, before ITV secured the broadcast rights which saw the return of the Olivier Awards to mainstream television in 2013.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> This has continued in recent years, and the ceremony has also been broadcast on [[Magic 105.4 FM|Magic Radio]]. \n\n==Award categories==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n\n===Drama===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Play|Best New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Revival|Best Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Comedy|Best New Comedy]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role|Best Performance in a Supporting Role]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n\n===Musical===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical|Best New Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Musical Revival|Best Musical Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Best Actress in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Actor in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Music|Outstanding Achievement in Music]]\n\n===Production===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Theatre Choreographer|Best Theatre Choreographer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Set Design|Best Set Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Lighting Design|Best Lighting Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Dance/Opera===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Dance Production|Best New Dance Production]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Opera Production|Best New Opera Production]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Dance|Outstanding Achievement in Dance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Opera|Outstanding Achievement in Opera]]\n\n===Other===\n* [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Award]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Entertainment|Best Entertainment and Family]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in an Affiliate Theatre|Outstanding Achievement in an Affiliate Theatre]]\n* [[Audience Award for Most Popular Show|Audience Award]]\n\n===Retired===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actor of the Year in a New Play|Actor of the Year in a New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a New Play|Actress of the Year in a New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actor of the Year in a Revival|Actor of the Year in a Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a Revival|Actress of the Year in a Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Comedy Performance|Best Comedy Performance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Musical|Best Performance in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Supporting Artist of the Year|Supporting Artist of the Year]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Newcomer in a Play|Best Newcomer in a Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Most Promising Performer|Most Promising Performer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Company Performance|Best Company Performance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director of a Play|Best Director of a Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director of a Musical|Best Director of a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Most Promising Playwright|Most Promising Playwright]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Set Designer|Best Set Designer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in a Musical|Outstanding Achievement in a Musical]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Award milestones==\nSome notable records and facts about the Laurence Olivier Awards include the following:<ref>[https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/10-things-probably-didnt-know-olivier-awards/ Olivier Awards: 10 Things You Probably Didn't Know]. OfficialLondonTheatre.com, accessed Jan 30, 2018</ref>\n\n===Productions===\n*The record for the most Olivier Awards ever received by a musical is tied with ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' in 2012 and ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' in 2018, both with seven awards each including Best New Musical.\n* The most Olivier Awards ever received by a play was ''[[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]]'' in 2017 with nine awards including Best New Play.\n* ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' (2013) received seven Olivier Awards. ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|Nicholas Nickleby]]'' (1980) received six. ''[[Chimerica (play)|Chimerica]]'' (2014), ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (2007), ''[[She Loves Me]]'' (1995) and ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982) received five. ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' (2016), ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]'' (2014), ''[[After the Dance (play)|After the Dance]]'' (2011), ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'' (2010), ''[[Black Watch (play)|Black Watch]]'' (2009), ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008), ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera|Jerry Springer]]'' (2004), ''[[All My Sons]]'' (2001), ''[[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliot]]'' (2006), ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' (2006), ''[[Oklahoma!|Oklahoma]]'' (1999), ''[[Stanley (play)|Stanley]]'' (1997), ''[[Machinal]]'' (1994), ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1994), ''[[An Inspector Calls]]'' (1993) and ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' (1993) received four.\n* The most nominations ever received by a production is 13 with ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' (2018). ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008) and ''[[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]]'' (2017) received 11. ''[[Follies]]'' (2018) had 10. ''[[Come from Away]]'' (2019), ''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' (2019), ''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]]'' (2015), ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' (2012), ''[[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliot]]'' (2006), ''[[Mary Poppins (musical)|Mary Poppins]]'' (2005), ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' (2002), ''[[Oklahoma!|Oklahoma]]'' (1999) and ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' (1993) received nine. ''[[The Inheritance (play)|The Inheritance]]'' (2019), ''[[The Ferryman (play)|The Ferryman]]'' (2018), ''[[Groundhog Day (musical)|Groundhog Day]]'' (2017), ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' (2016), ''[[Beautiful: The Carole King Musical]]'' (2015), ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' (2013), ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' (2005), ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (2006),  ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera|Jerry Springer]]'' (2004), ''[[Pacific Overtures]]'' (2004), ''[[Ragtime (musical)|Ragtime]]'' (2004), ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2002), ''[[Spend Spend Spend|Spend, Spend, Spend]]'' (2000), ''[[The Lion King (musical)|The Lion King]]'' (2000), ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]'' (1997) and ''[[She Loves Me]]'' (1995) received eight.\n*''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' (2002) holds the record for most nominations without any wins at nine. \n*Tim Flavin was the first American actor to win the Laurence Olivier Award for his performance in On Your Toes at the Palace Theatre in 1984. Tim was nominated twice in the same year for Most Promising Newcomer and Best Actor in a Musical. His award was presented to him by Dame Anna Neagle.\n\n===Individuals===\n*  [[William Dudley (designer)|William Dudley]] (designer), [[Judi Dench]] (actress) and [[Matthew Bourne]] (choreographer) are tied for the record for the most competitive wins by an individual with seven each. Dench also won a [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Olivier Award]] in 2004. [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] (composer/producer) has won six plus the Special Olivier Award in 2008.<ref>[http://www.reallyuseful.com/news/andrew-lloyd-webber-receives-seventh-olivier \"Andrew Lloyd Webber Receives Seventh Olivier\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213074745/http://www.reallyuseful.com/news/andrew-lloyd-webber-receives-seventh-olivier/ |date=2012-02-13 }}. Really Useful Group</ref>\n* [[Ian McKellen]], [[Alan Bennett]], [[Richard Eyre]] and [[Stephen Sondheim]] have all won five competitive awards plus the Special Olivier Award.\n* Five wins: [[Declan Donnellan]], [[Mark Henderson (lighting designer)|Mark Henderson]], Mark Thompson.\n* Four wins: [[Michael Bryant (actor)|Michael Bryant]], [[Darcey Bussell]], [[Michael Frayn]], [[Michael Gambon]], [[Tim Goodchild]], [[Clare Higgins]], [[Alex Jennings]], [[Sam Mendes]], [[John Napier]], [[Trevor Nunn]], [[Philip Quast]], [[Willy Russell]], [[Simon Russell Beale]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Frances de la Tour]], [[Paule Constable]].\n* Performers who have won Olivier Awards in both the play and musical categories are: [[Simon Russell Beale]], [[Jonathan Pryce]], [[Henry Goodman]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Judi Dench]], [[Sheridan Smith]], [[Janie Dee]] and [[Sharon D. Clarke]].\n* [[Maggie Smith]] has never won the award despite being nominated a total of six times. She did receive the [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Olivier Award]] in 2010.\n* [[Judi Dench]] is the only actress to win dramatic and musical Olivier acting awards in the same year (1996) - for her performances in ''Absolute Hell'' and ''[[A Little Night Music]]''.\n* [[Philip Quast]] has won the Olivier for Best Actor in a Musical on three occasions, while [[Michael Crawford]], [[Robert Lindsay (actor)|Robert Lindsay]], [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Michael Ball]] have all won the award twice.\n* [[Imelda Staunton]] has won the Olivier for Best Actress in a Musical three times. [[Julia McKenzie]], [[Joanna Riding]], [[Maria Friedman]] and [[Samantha Spiro]] have all won twice. Imelda Staunton also holds the record for the most Olivier nominations in the Best Actress in a Musical category, with seven nominations. Maria Friedman is next, with six nominations.\n* [[Jenny Galloway]] and [[Tracie Bennett]] have both won the Olivier for Best Supporting Performance in a Musical twice.\n* Shows that have won Olivier Awards for Best Actor and Best Actress in a Musical: [[Barbara Dickson]] and [[Con O'Neill (actor)|Con O'Neill]] in ''[[Blood Brothers (musical)|Blood Brothers]]'' (1988), [[Jonathan Pryce]] and [[Lea Salonga]] in ''[[Miss Saigon]]'' (1990), [[Alun Armstrong (actor)|Alun Armstrong]] and [[Julia McKenzie]] in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1993), [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Samantha Spiro]] in ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]'' (2001), [[Alex Jennings]] and [[Joanna Riding]] in ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2003), [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Jenna Russell]] in ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (2007), [[Michael Ball]] and [[Leanne Jones]] in ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008), [[Bertie Carvel]] and all four Matildas in ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' (2012) and [[Michael Ball]] and [[Imelda Staunton]] in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (2013)\n* [[Jessica Lange]] is the first American actress nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for Best Actress for her performance in ''[[Long Day's Journey Into Night]]''\n* ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' won all three musical acting awards in 2008: Best Actor and Actress in a Musical for [[Michael Ball]] and [[Leanne Jones]] and Best Supporting Performance in a Musical for [[Tracie Bennett]].\n* Roles that have won awards for actors on more than one occasion include: Miss Adelaide in ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982 and 2006), George in ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (1991 and 2007), The Baker's Wife in ''[[Into the Woods]]'' (1991 and 1999), Nicely Nicely Johnson in ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982 and 1997), Sweeney Todd in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1980, 1994 and 2013), Mrs. Lovett in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1980, 1994 and 2013), Frau Schneider in ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' (1994 and 2007) and Eliza Doolittle in ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2002 and 2003).\n* [[Michael Ball]] and [[Bertie Carvel]] both won Oliviers for playing roles of the opposite sex, in 2008 for ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' and 2012 for ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'', respectively.\n* Shared wins: In 2006, all three actors sharing the role of Billy Elliot received the Olivier for Best Actor in a Musical and in 2012, all four actresses sharing the role of Matilda received the Olivier for Best Actress in a Musical.\n* Shared nominations: In 2017, the eight members of the cast of [[Our Ladies of Perpetual Succour|''Our Ladies Of Perpetual Succour'']] were jointly nominated for Best Actress in a Supporting Role and in the same year, six cast members from [[The Girls (musical)|''The Girls'']] were jointly nominated in the Best Actress in a Musical category. In 2019, the six cast members of [[Six (musical)|''Six'']] were jointly nominated for Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical for their performances as the six wives of Henry VIII. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/winners/olivier-winners-2017/|title=Olivier Winners 2017|work=Olivier Awards|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*In 2012 [[Eleanor Worthington Cox|Eleanor Worthington-Cox]] won for her role Matilda in Matilda and with that she became youngest winner of this prize.\n* In 1985, [[Patti LuPone]] became the first American actress to win an Olivier award for her work in [[The Cradle Will Rock]] and [[Les Miserables]].\n* In 2018, [[Billie Piper]] became the first, and so far only, actor to have won all six of the currently available UK Theatre Best Actress awards for a single performance (Evening Standard Theatre Awards, What's On Stage Theatre Awards, Critic's Circle Theatre Awards, Broadway UK Theatre Awards, Glamour Awards and Laurence Olivier Theatre Awards. This accolade was achieved by her performance in Yerma which was hailed as \u201cthe performance of the decade\u201d, \u201cshattering, exhausting, earthquaking\u201d and \u201cunbearably harrowing\u201d. <ref>http://www.billiepiperofficial.com/about</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ian Charleson Award]]\n*[[West End theatre]]\n*[[Evening Standard Theatre Award]]\n*[[Tony Award]]\n*[[Drama Desk Award]]\n*[[List of Tony Award and Olivier Award winning musicals]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{official website|http://www.olivierawards.com/home/}}\n\n{{Olivier Awards}}\n{{Laurence Olivier}}\n\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Awards| ]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier]]\n[[Category:Stagecraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name        = The Olivier Awards\n| current_awards = 2020 Laurence Olivier Awards\n| image       = \n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Laurence Olivier Award, designed by the sculptor Harry Franchetti.  It depicts Olivier as Henry V at the [[Old Vic]] in 1937.\n| description = Best in London theatre\n| presenter   = [[Society of London Theatre]]\n| country     = [[United Kingdom]]\n| year        = {{start date and age|1976}}\n| website     = https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/\n}}\n\nThe '''Laurence Olivier Awards''', or simply the '''Olivier Awards''', are presented annually by the [[Society of London Theatre]] to recognise excellence in professional theatre in [[London]] at an annual ceremony in the capital. The awards were originally known as the '''Society of West End Theatre Awards''', but they were renamed in honour of the British actor [[Laurence Olivier]] in 1984.\n\nThe awards are given to individuals involved in [[West End theatre|West End]] productions and other leading [[West End theatre#London's non-commercial theatres|non-commercial theatres]] based in London across a range of categories covering plays, musicals, dance, opera and affiliate theatre. A discretionary non-competitive Special Olivier Award is also given each year. The Olivier Awards are recognised internationally as the highest honour in British theatre, equivalent to the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] Awards for film and television, and the [[Brit Awards|BRIT Awards]] for music. The Olivier Awards are considered equivalent to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]'s [[Tony Award]]s and [[France]]'s [[Moli\u00e8re Award]].\n\nSince its inception, the awards have been held at various venues and theatres across London, from 2012-2016 at the [[Royal Opera House]], before moving to the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 2017. Television coverage is broadcast in prime time on ITV, who acquired the rights from 2013 onwards with radio coverage by [[Magic Radio (London radio station)|Magic Radio]].\n\n==History==\nThe awards were first established in 1976 by the Society of London Theatre as the Society of West End Awards and were designed by artist Tom Merrifield. In 1984, British actor [[Laurence Olivier]] gave his consent for the awards to be renamed in his honour and they became known as the Laurence Olivier Awards.<ref>[https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/10-things-probably-didnt-know-olivier-awards/ \"10 Things You Probably Didn't Know About The Olivier Awards\"]. OfficialLondonTheatre.com, accessed 30 January 2018</ref> The [[1976 Laurence Olivier Awards|first awards ceremony]] was held in December 1976 at [[Hotel Caf\u00e9 Royal|Caf\u00e9 Royal]].\n\n==Judging==\nEach year, Olivier Awards judging panels for theatre, opera, dance and affiliate shows are put together by the [[Society of London Theatre|Society of London Theatre (SOLT)]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/choosing-the-winners/|title=How the Olivier Award winners are chosen - Olivier Awards|work=Official London Theatre|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nFor opera, dance and affiliates, each panel are made up of a mix of \u2018professional\u2019 panellists (journalists, casting directors, arts administrators, publishers and other industry professionals chosen for their knowledge in the field) and members of the public who are passionate about London theatre. The panels first select the shows they consider most worthy of an Olivier Award nomination, then vote on a winner at the end of the judging period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFor the theatre awards, a longlist is compiled by a panel made up of members of the public, and submitted to SOLT members to vote on. Members may still vote outside of the list at this stage, except for in the four Supporting Actor/Actress categories (as these each contain thousands of eligible performers). The members\u2019 votes are collated with those of the panellists to create the list of nominees. The nominees list is then voted on by both members and panellists to produce the winners.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Ceremony==\n\n===Hosts and Presenters===\nPrevious hosts of the Olivier Awards ceremony include [[Michael Ball]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Clive Anderson]], [[Gemma Arterton]], [[Stephen Mangan]], [[Hugh Bonneville]], [[Sheridan Smith]], [[Lenny Henry]], [[Catherine Tate]] and [[Jason Manford]].\n\nPresenters of individual awards include [[Anthony Head]], [[James Nesbitt]], [[Richard E. Grant]], [[Richard Wilson (Scottish actor)|Richard Wilson]], [[Sue Johnston]], [[Angela Lansbury]], [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], [[Eddie Izzard]], Sir [[Tom Stoppard]], [[Barry Norman]], [[Peter Barkworth]], [[Daniel Radcliffe]], [[Anthony Hopkins]], [[Sue Lawley]], [[Diana Rigg]], [[Edward Fox (actor)|Edward Fox]], [[Tim Rice]], [[Gary Wilmot]], [[Jane Asher]], [[Tom Conti]], [[Denis Quilley]], [[Angela Rippon]], [[Cuba Gooding Jr.]], [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]], [[Patti LuPone]], [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]], [[John Boyega]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Meera Syal]], [[Paul O'Grady]], [[Julian Clary]] and [[Juliet Stevenson]].<ref name=facts>[http://www.olivierawards.com/about/facts-and-trivia/ \"Olivier Awards Facts\"]. Olivierawards.com, accessed 7 February 2011</ref>\n\n===Venues===\nThe venue most associated with the Awards is [[Grosvenor House Hotel]], which has housed the after-show reception nine times and hosted the whole event on four further occasions. As well as at the Grosvenor, the presentations have been held at: Victoria Palace, Lyceum, National Theatre Olivier, Albery (now No\u00ebl Coward), Shaftesbury, London Palladium, Dominion, Royalty, [[Theatre Royal Drury Lane]],<ref name=playbill>Jones, Kenneth. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147401-Love-Never-Dies-Legally-Blonde-Rylance-Jacobi-Boggess-Bennett-End-of-the-Rainbow-Are-Olivier-Nominees \"Love Never Dies, Legally Blonde, Rylance, Jacobi, Boggess, Bennett, End of the Rainbow Are Olivier Nominees\"]. Playbill.com, February 7, 2011</ref> Caf\u00e9 Royal, Piccadilly, and The Park Lane Hilton.\n\nFrom [[2012 Laurence Olivier Awards|2012 to 2016]] the awards ceremony was held at the [[Royal Opera House]], moving to the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in 2017.<ref name=\"Who Won at The Olivier Awards 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/the-olivier-awards-2017 | title= Who Won at The Olivier Awards 2017 | publisher=Ikon London Magazine | last1 = Alvarez | first1 = Joe | last2 = Orlova-Alvarez | first2 = Tamara | date=10 April 2017 | accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/how-it-all-began/|title=Olivier Awards - How It All Began|website=OfficialLondonTheatre.com|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref> The 2013 ceremony was the first ceremony to be broadcast on television since 2003.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/jan/29/olivier-awards-return-to-tv|title=Olivier awards make triumphant return to TV|first=Matt|last=Trueman|date=29 January 2013|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe first Laurence Olivier Awards to be broadcast on television was the 1981 ceremony, which was broadcast on BBC1, and continued every year until 1992, before switching to BBC2 each year until 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westendtheatre.com/16310/the-olivier-awards/awards-history/|title=Olivier Awards \u2013 HistoryLondon theatre tickets - London theatre tickets|website=www.westendtheatre.com}}</ref> The awards ceremony was then only broadcast on radio until 2011, when the BBC broadcast live interactive red-button coverage of the event,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2011/mar/14/olivier-awards-bbc-coverage-ceremony|title=Olivier theatre awards: the BBC should be red-faced over its red-button coverage|first=Carrie|last=Dunn|date=14 March 2011|website=the Guardian}}</ref> while [[Paul Gambaccini]] presented a programme on [[BBC Radio 2]] with live coverage and interviews.<ref name=playbill/> The same coverage followed in 2012, before ITV secured the broadcast rights which saw the return of the Olivier Awards to mainstream television in 2013.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> This has continued in recent years, and the ceremony has also been broadcast on [[Magic 105.4 FM|Magic Radio]]. \n\n==Award categories==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n\n===Drama===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Play|Best New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Revival|Best Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Comedy|Best New Comedy]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role|Best Performance in a Supporting Role]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role|Best Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n\n===Musical===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical|Best New Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Musical Revival|Best Musical Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical|Best Actor in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Best Actress in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Performance in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Actor in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n** [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical|Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Music|Outstanding Achievement in Music]]\n\n===Production===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Theatre Choreographer|Best Theatre Choreographer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Set Design|Best Set Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Lighting Design|Best Lighting Design]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Dance/Opera===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Dance Production|Best New Dance Production]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Opera Production|Best New Opera Production]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Dance|Outstanding Achievement in Dance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in Opera|Outstanding Achievement in Opera]]\n\n===Other===\n* [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Award]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Entertainment|Best Entertainment and Family]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in an Affiliate Theatre|Outstanding Achievement in an Affiliate Theatre]]\n* [[Audience Award for Most Popular Show|Audience Award]]\n\n===Retired===\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actor of the Year in a New Play|Actor of the Year in a New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a New Play|Actress of the Year in a New Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actor of the Year in a Revival|Actor of the Year in a Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Actress of the Year in a Revival|Actress of the Year in a Revival]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Comedy Performance|Best Comedy Performance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Musical|Best Performance in a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Supporting Artist of the Year|Supporting Artist of the Year]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Newcomer in a Play|Best Newcomer in a Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Most Promising Performer|Most Promising Performer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Company Performance|Best Company Performance]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director of a Play|Best Director of a Play]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Director of a Musical|Best Director of a Musical]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Most Promising Playwright|Most Promising Playwright]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Set Designer|Best Set Designer]]\n* [[Laurence Olivier Award for Outstanding Achievement in a Musical|Outstanding Achievement in a Musical]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Award milestones==\nSome notable records and facts about the Laurence Olivier Awards include the following:<ref>[https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/10-things-probably-didnt-know-olivier-awards/ Olivier Awards: 10 Things You Probably Didn't Know]. OfficialLondonTheatre.com, accessed Jan 30, 2018</ref>\n\n===Productions===\n*The record for the most Olivier Awards ever received by a musical is tied with ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' in 2012 and ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' in 2018, both with seven awards each including Best New Musical.\n* The most Olivier Awards ever received by a play was ''[[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]]'' in 2017 with nine awards including Best New Play.\n* ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' (2013) received seven Olivier Awards. ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby (play)|Nicholas Nickleby]]'' (1980) received six. ''[[Chimerica (play)|Chimerica]]'' (2014), ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (2007), ''[[She Loves Me]]'' (1995) and ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982) received five. ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' (2016), ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]'' (2014), ''[[After the Dance (play)|After the Dance]]'' (2011), ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'' (2010), ''[[Black Watch (play)|Black Watch]]'' (2009), ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008), ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera|Jerry Springer]]'' (2004), ''[[All My Sons]]'' (2001), ''[[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliot]]'' (2006), ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'' (2006), ''[[Oklahoma!|Oklahoma]]'' (1999), ''[[Stanley (play)|Stanley]]'' (1997), ''[[Machinal]]'' (1994), ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1994), ''[[An Inspector Calls]]'' (1993) and ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' (1993) received four.\n* The most nominations ever received by a production is 13 with ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' (2018). ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008) and ''[[Harry Potter and the Cursed Child]]'' (2017) received 11. ''[[Follies]]'' (2018) had 10. ''[[Come from Away]]'' (2019), ''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' (2019), ''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]]'' (2015), ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' (2012), ''[[Billy Elliot the Musical|Billy Elliot]]'' (2006), ''[[Mary Poppins (musical)|Mary Poppins]]'' (2005), ''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' (2002), ''[[Oklahoma!|Oklahoma]]'' (1999) and ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'' (1993) received nine. ''[[The Inheritance (play)|The Inheritance]]'' (2019), ''[[The Ferryman (play)|The Ferryman]]'' (2018), ''[[Groundhog Day (musical)|Groundhog Day]]'' (2017), ''[[Gypsy (musical)|Gypsy]]'' (2016), ''[[Beautiful: The Carole King Musical]]'' (2015), ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' (2013), ''[[The Producers (musical)|The Producers]]'' (2005), ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (2006),  ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera|Jerry Springer]]'' (2004), ''[[Pacific Overtures]]'' (2004), ''[[Ragtime (musical)|Ragtime]]'' (2004), ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2002), ''[[Spend Spend Spend|Spend, Spend, Spend]]'' (2000), ''[[The Lion King (musical)|The Lion King]]'' (2000), ''[[The Who's Tommy|Tommy]]'' (1997) and ''[[She Loves Me]]'' (1995) received eight.\n*''[[Kiss Me, Kate]]'' (2002) holds the record for most nominations without any wins at nine.\n\n===Individuals===\n*  [[William Dudley (designer)|William Dudley]] (designer), [[Judi Dench]] (actress) and [[Matthew Bourne]] (choreographer) are tied for the record for the most competitive wins by an individual with seven each. Dench also won a [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Olivier Award]] in 2004. [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] (composer/producer) has won six plus the Special Olivier Award in 2008.<ref>[http://www.reallyuseful.com/news/andrew-lloyd-webber-receives-seventh-olivier \"Andrew Lloyd Webber Receives Seventh Olivier\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213074745/http://www.reallyuseful.com/news/andrew-lloyd-webber-receives-seventh-olivier/ |date=2012-02-13 }}. Really Useful Group</ref>\n* [[Ian McKellen]], [[Alan Bennett]], [[Richard Eyre]] and [[Stephen Sondheim]] have all won five competitive awards plus the Special Olivier Award.\n* Five wins: [[Declan Donnellan]], [[Mark Henderson (lighting designer)|Mark Henderson]], Mark Thompson.\n* Four wins: [[Michael Bryant (actor)|Michael Bryant]], [[Darcey Bussell]], [[Michael Frayn]], [[Michael Gambon]], [[Tim Goodchild]], [[Clare Higgins]], [[Alex Jennings]], [[Sam Mendes]], [[John Napier]], [[Trevor Nunn]], [[Philip Quast]], [[Willy Russell]], [[Simon Russell Beale]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Frances de la Tour]], [[Paule Constable]].\n* Performers who have won Olivier Awards in both the play and musical categories are: [[Simon Russell Beale]], [[Jonathan Pryce]], [[Henry Goodman]], [[Imelda Staunton]], [[Judi Dench]], [[Sheridan Smith]], [[Janie Dee]] and [[Sharon D. Clarke]].\n* [[Maggie Smith]] has never won the award despite being nominated a total of six times. She did receive the [[Society of London Theatre Special Award|Special Olivier Award]] in 2010.\n* [[Judi Dench]] is the only actress to win dramatic and musical Olivier acting awards in the same year (1996) - for her performances in ''Absolute Hell'' and ''[[A Little Night Music]]''.\n* [[Philip Quast]] has won the Olivier for Best Actor in a Musical on three occasions, while [[Michael Crawford]], [[Robert Lindsay (actor)|Robert Lindsay]], [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Michael Ball]] have all won the award twice.\n* [[Imelda Staunton]] has won the Olivier for Best Actress in a Musical three times. [[Julia McKenzie]], [[Joanna Riding]], [[Maria Friedman]] and [[Samantha Spiro]] have all won twice. Imelda Staunton also holds the record for the most Olivier nominations in the Best Actress in a Musical category, with seven nominations. Maria Friedman is next, with six nominations.\n* [[Jenny Galloway]] and [[Tracie Bennett]] have both won the Olivier for Best Supporting Performance in a Musical twice.\n* Shows that have won Olivier Awards for Best Actor and Best Actress in a Musical: [[Barbara Dickson]] and [[Con O'Neill (actor)|Con O'Neill]] in ''[[Blood Brothers (musical)|Blood Brothers]]'' (1988), [[Jonathan Pryce]] and [[Lea Salonga]] in ''[[Miss Saigon]]'' (1990), [[Alun Armstrong (actor)|Alun Armstrong]] and [[Julia McKenzie]] in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1993), [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Samantha Spiro]] in ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]'' (2001), [[Alex Jennings]] and [[Joanna Riding]] in ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2003), [[Daniel Evans (actor)|Daniel Evans]] and [[Jenna Russell]] in ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (2007), [[Michael Ball]] and [[Leanne Jones]] in ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' (2008), [[Bertie Carvel]] and all four Matildas in ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'' (2012) and [[Michael Ball]] and [[Imelda Staunton]] in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (2013)\n* [[Jessica Lange]] is the first American actress nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for Best Actress for her performance in ''[[Long Day's Journey Into Night]]''\n* ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' won all three musical acting awards in 2008: Best Actor and Actress in a Musical for [[Michael Ball]] and [[Leanne Jones]] and Best Supporting Performance in a Musical for [[Tracie Bennett]].\n* Roles that have won awards for actors on more than one occasion include: Miss Adelaide in ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982 and 2006), George in ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (1991 and 2007), The Baker's Wife in ''[[Into the Woods]]'' (1991 and 1999), Nicely Nicely Johnson in ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' (1982 and 1997), Sweeney Todd in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1980, 1994 and 2013), Mrs. Lovett in ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]'' (1980, 1994 and 2013), Frau Schneider in ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' (1994 and 2007) and Eliza Doolittle in ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' (2002 and 2003).\n* [[Michael Ball]] and [[Bertie Carvel]] both won Oliviers for playing roles of the opposite sex, in 2008 for ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'' and 2012 for ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]'', respectively.\n* Shared wins: In 2006, all three actors sharing the role of Billy Elliot received the Olivier for Best Actor in a Musical and in 2012, all four actresses sharing the role of Matilda received the Olivier for Best Actress in a Musical.\n* Shared nominations: In 2017, the eight members of the cast of [[Our Ladies of Perpetual Succour|''Our Ladies Of Perpetual Succour'']] were jointly nominated for Best Actress in a Supporting Role and in the same year, six cast members from [[The Girls (musical)|''The Girls'']] were jointly nominated in the Best Actress in a Musical category. In 2019, the six cast members of [[Six (musical)|''Six'']] were jointly nominated for Best Actress in a Supporting Role in a Musical for their performances as the six wives of Henry VIII. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/winners/olivier-winners-2017/|title=Olivier Winners 2017|work=Olivier Awards|access-date=2018-01-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*In 2012 [[Eleanor Worthington Cox|Eleanor Worthington-Cox]] won for her role Matilda in Matilda and with that she became youngest winner of this prize.\n* In 1985, [[Patti LuPone]] became the first American actress to win an Olivier award for her work in [[The Cradle Will Rock]] and [[Les Miserables]].\n* In 2018, [[Billie Piper]] became the first, and so far only, actor to have won all six of the currently available UK Theatre Best Actress awards for a single performance (Evening Standard Theatre Awards, What's On Stage Theatre Awards, Critic's Circle Theatre Awards, Broadway UK Theatre Awards, Glamour Awards and Laurence Olivier Theatre Awards. This accolade was achieved by her performance in Yerma which was hailed as \u201cthe performance of the decade\u201d, \u201cshattering, exhausting, earthquaking\u201d and \u201cunbearably harrowing\u201d. <ref>http://www.billiepiperofficial.com/about</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ian Charleson Award]]\n*[[West End theatre]]\n*[[Evening Standard Theatre Award]]\n*[[Tony Award]]\n*[[Drama Desk Award]]\n*[[List of Tony Award and Olivier Award winning musicals]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{official website|http://www.olivierawards.com/home/}}\n\n{{Olivier Awards}}\n{{Laurence Olivier}}\n\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Awards| ]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier]]\n[[Category:Stagecraft]]\n", "name_user": "Tim Flavin", "label": "safe", "comment": "An addition of fact was contributed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurence_Olivier_Award"}
